{{Infobox famine | name = 1921–22 famine in Tatarstan | native_name = <!-- Name of the famine in local language --> | image = Victims of the 1921 famine in Russia.jpg | alt = <!-- Image [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = Victims of the famine in Buzuluk, 1921 | country = [[Soviet Union]] | location = [[Tatar ASSR]] | coordinates = <!-- (use {{coord}}) --> | period = 1921–1922 | excess_mortality = <!-- Deaths directly due to famine starvation --> | from_disease = <!-- Indirect famine deaths from subsequent diseases --> | total_deaths = 500,000{{sfn|Dronin|Bellinger|2005|p=98}}–2,000,000{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=281}} | death_rate = <!-- Death rate --> | observations = Failures of collectivization <!-- Examples: policy failure, war, drought, potato blight, back-to-back poor harvests, genocide, etc --> | theory = <!-- Examples: food availability decline (FAD - conventional), failure of exchange entitlements (FEE - Amartya Sen), Anti-famine contract (De Waal), Malthus, etc --> | relief = Aid provided by the ''Tatpomgol'', [[Workers International Relief]], and [[American Relief Administration]]<!-- Examples: 1 million tons of grain, no relief, etc --> | food_situation = <!-- Net food imports, examples: 10 million tons of wheat, can be negative for repressive regimes/genocide cases --> | demographics = 10% of the Tatar ASSR population died while another 13% fled to other parts of the country | consequences = <!-- Political consequences, example: Indian independence movement intensified due to a lack of relief or allegations of genocide were made, etc --> | memorial = <!-- link to the memorial website --> | preceded = [[Russian famine of 1891–92]] | succeeded = [[Soviet famine of 1932–33]] }}
The '''1921–1922 famine in Tatarstan''' was a period of mass starvation and drought that took place in the [[Tatar Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Tatar ASSR]] as a result of [[war communism]] policy,{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=18}}<ref>{{Citation|title=The Black Book of Communism: Crimes, Terror, Repression|date=October 1999|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H1jsgYCoRioC|last1=Werth|last2=Panné|last3=Paczkowski|last4=Bartosek|last5=Margolin|first1=Nicolas|first2=Jean-Louis|first3=Andrzej|first4=Karel|first5=Jean-Louis|author1-link=Nicolas Werth|author3-link=Andrzej Paczkowski|pages=92–97; 116–21|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|editor-last=Courtois|editor-first=Stéphane|editor-link=Stéphane Courtois|isbn=978-0-674-07608-2}}</ref> in which 500,000{{sfn|Dronin|Bellinger|2005|p=98}} to 2,000,000{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=281}} peasants died. The event was part of the greater [[Russian famine of 1921–22]] that affected other parts of the [[Soviet Union|USSR]],{{sfn|Millar|2004|p=56}} in which up 5,000,000 people died in total.{{sfn|Millar|2004|p=270}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.stanford.edu/pr/2011/pr-famine-040411.html|title=How the U.S. saved a starving Soviet Russia: PBS film highlights Stanford scholar's research on the 1921-23 famine|last=Haven|first=Cynthia|date=4 April 2011|website=Stanford News Service|language=|access-date=28 April 2017}}</ref> According to [[Roman Serbyn]], a professor of Russian and East European history, the Tatarstan famine was the first man-made famine in the Soviet Union and systematically targeted ethnic minorities such as [[Volga Tatars]] and [[Volga Germans]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Serbyn|first1=Roman|title=The first man-made famine in Soviet Union 1921-1923|url=http://www.ukrweekly.com/old/archive/1988/458814.shtml|website=The Ukrainian Weekly|accessdate=28 April 2017|date=6 November 1988}}</ref>
==Background== Soviet leadership had long sought to suppress [[Tatar nationalism]] in the USSR. Tatars were frequently charged with "[[bourgeois nationalism]]" and other revisionist crimes. Tatar leadership was executed or imprisoned, which many fled the USSR to Turkey for refuge. Collectivization of Tatar agriculture began in 1921. According to historian James Minahan, [[Crimean Tatars]] in particular "suffered proportionally greater population losses than any other Soviet national group during the first decades of Soviet rule."<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wXejvEgKs9oC&pg=PA164|title=The Former Soviet Union's Diverse Peoples: A Reference Sourcebook|last=Minahan|first=James|date=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=|isbn=9781576078235|location=|pages=164|language=}}</ref> Farming methods in the Tatar ASSR were outdated, similar to most non-Russian nationalities in the Soviet Union. In addition, very few indigenous Tatar proletariat existed due to Russian imperial dominance.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=154}}
==Famine== In early spring of 1921, the [[Cheka]] reported massive protests and riots among peasants. By 23 March, reports began to describe the developments in some kantons as a "famine" and documented peasants starving to death and committing suicide. In response to the lack of food, many peasants prevented grain trucks from leaving Tatarstan and some refused to sow their fields.{{sfn|Dronin|Bellinger|2005|p=98}} The famine also saw a large rise in the number of children submitted to orphanages, with poorer parents leaving their children in state institutions and some just abandoning them on the streets to fend for themselves. Orphanages could not keep up with demand, and the Tatar ASSR government devoted resources to expand the number of institutions available. For example, the [[Sviyazhsk]] [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Tatarstan|kanton]] had two orphanages, which kept 64 children in July 1920. By, January 1922, this had expanded to 12 orphanages with 704 children.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fjodorova|first1=Natalia A.|last2=Khanipova|first2=Ilnara I.|title=Struggle Against Homelessness and Neglect in Tatar ASSR in 1920s – The First Half of 1940s|journal=Mediterranean Journal of Social Sciences|date=November 2015|volume=6|issue=6 S2|page=476|doi=10.5901/mjss.2015.v6n6s2p475|url=http://www.mcser.org/journal/index.php/mjss/article/viewFile/8120/7784|publisher=MCSER Publishing|location=Rome, Italy|issn=2039-2117}}</ref>
By March 1922, some villages had lost half their population.{{sfn|Dronin|Bellinger|2005|p=100}} The famine also led to a sharp decline in the number of livestock and farming equipment as starving peasants sold off their property or slaughtered the draft animals for food.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=3}} KGB records from the time note the deaths of at least 500,000 people in Tatarstan,{{sfn|Dronin|Bellinger|2005|p=98}} but more recent estimates conclude the actual value was much higher at 2,000,000.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=281}} Historian James Long approximates that roughly 13% of the Tatar ASSR population fled to other parts of the country while another 10% died.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=2}} This famine is also known as "terror-famine" and "famine-genocide" in Tatarstan.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
==Relief== In the summer of 1922, the special committee ''Tatpomgol'' was established to cope with the famine.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=176}} By August 1922, ''Tatpomgol'' imported 8 million [[pood]] (Russian pounds) of food, including 2 million pounds of seed, with a loan.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=184}} From the affected regions, hundreds of thousands of people, mostly children, were evacuated to [[Central Asia]], [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Belarus]] and [[Siberia]].{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=206}} Emergency feeding points were established throughout the republic.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=230}} The [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] government invited international organizations, such as [[Workers International Relief]] to assist.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SlRc3KqcDygC&pg=PA176|title=American Communism and Soviet Russia|last=Draper|first=Theodore|date=1960|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=|isbn=9781412816915|location=|pages=176|language=en}}</ref> The United States government provided aid to starving Tatars in from 1920 to 1923 through the [[American Relief Administration]].{{sfn|Millar|2004|p=56}}
==Aftermath== Though the most hard-hitting phase of the famine ended in 1922, shortages, starvation, and illness continued in the Volga region throughout 1923 and into 1924,{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=3}} and the Soviet government settled ethnic [[Russians]] into the Tatar ASSR and in [[Idel-Ural]] region in this time causing the Tatars' share of the population to eventually decline to less than 50%.{{sfn|Mizelle|2002|p=304}}
In 2008, the [[All-Russian Tatar Social Center]] (VTOTs) asked the [[United Nations]] to condemn the 1921–22 Tatarstan famine as [[genocide]] of [[Muslim]] Tatars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=|title=Tatar Nationalists Ask UN to condemn 1921 famine as genocide|last=Globe|first=Paul|date=6 November 2008|website=Homin Ukraini}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chaudet|first=Didier|date=June 2009|title=When the Bear Confronts the Crescent: Russia and the Jihadist Issue|url=https://www.files.ethz.ch/isn/105451/CEFQ200905.pdf|journal=The China and Eurasia Forum Quarterly|publisher=Central Asia-Caucasus Institute & Silk Road Studies Program|volume=7|issue=2|pages=49}}</ref>
