'''Guido Valadares National Hospital''' ({{lang-pt|Hospital Nacional Guido Valadares}}), formerly '''Dili National Hospital''',  is the national hospital of East Timor. It is located in the eastern part of the capital city of [[Dili]]. In 2003 the hospital{{clarify|date=June 2014}} was renamed after [[Guido Valadares]], who was a government official of the [[Fretilin]] government in 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfac.gov.tp/localnews/local030630.html|title=Dili, June 30, 2003|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation|accessdate=16 July 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031108111314/http://www.mfac.gov.tp/localnews/local030630.html|archivedate=8 November 2003|df=}}</ref> As of 2011 it had 260 beds, with secondary and tertiary healthcare services.<ref name="Ghodse2011">{{cite book|last=Ghodse|first=Hamid|title=International Perspectives on Mental Health|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M_y2iFtKRoUC&pg=PA220|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=30 June 2011|publisher=RCPsych Publications|isbn=978-1-908020-00-0|page=220}}</ref> The hospital treats medical obstetric and surgical patients. On the site of the hospital there is also a major facility for eye diseases. Dialysis is offered within the department of medicine. There is a department of anaesthetics with an intensive care unit

