{{redirect-distinguish|Hyperthymia|hyperthermia}} {{More citations needed|date=June 2010}} '''Hyperthymic temperament''', or '''hyperthymia''', from Greek ''hyper'' ("over", meaning here ''excessive'') + [[Thumos|θυμός]] ("spirited"), is a proposed personality type characterized by an exceptionally positive mood and disposition. It is generally defined by increased energy, vividness and enthusiasm for life activities as opposed to dysthymia. Hyperthymia is similar to but more stable than [[hypomania]] with complete absence of irritability or negative mood effects.<ref name="wiktionary">{{cite web|url=http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/hyperthymia|title=hyperthymia - Wiktionary|publisher=en.wiktionary.org|accessdate=2015-05-13}}</ref><ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Concise Guide to Mood Disorders|author1=Dubovsky, S.L.|author2=Dubovsky, A.N.|date=2008|publisher=American Psychiatric Publishing|isbn=9781585627653|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qC2umbulUIwC|page=39|accessdate=2015-05-13}}</ref>
Characteristics of the hyperthymic temperament include:<ref>http://www.medscape.org/viewarticle/418724{{subscription needed}}{{clarify|date=November 2015}}</ref> * increased energy and [[productivity]] * short sleep patterns * vividness, activity [[Extraversion and introversion|extroversion]] * self-assurance, self-confidence * strong will * extreme talkativeness * tendency to repeat oneself * [[risk]]-taking/sensation seeking * breaking [[Norm (sociology)|social norms]] * very strong [[libido]] * love of attention * low threshold for [[boredom]] * generosity and tendency to overspend * emotion sensitivity * cheerfulness and joviality * unusual warmth * expansiveness * tirelessness * irrepressibility, irresistible, and infectious quality
The clinical, psychiatric understanding of hyperthymia is evolving. Studies have shown that hyperthymic temperament promotes efficient performance of complex tasks under time pressure or extreme conditions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jaracz |first1=Marcin |last2=Paciorek |first2=Przemysław |last3=Buciński |first3=Adam |last4=Borkowska |first4=Alina |title=Affective temperament and executive functions in emergency medicine professionals |journal=Journal of Affective Disorders |volume=168 |issue= |pages=192–6 |year=2014 |pmid=25063957 |doi=10.1016/j.jad.2014.07.004 }}</ref> Despite this positive characterization, hyperthymia can be complicated with depressive episodes manifesting as a softer form of bipolar illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medscape.org/viewarticle/439472_5|title=Beyond Antidepressants: Bipolar Spectrum Illness Presenting as Complicated or Refractory Mood Disorders in Primary Care|last=Manning|first=J. Sloan|date=|website=www.medscape.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manning|first=J. Sloan|date=February 2000|title=Refractory Depressed and Anxious States in Hyperthymic Women: A Case Series Generated by a Speaking Engagement|pmc=181104|journal=Primary Care Companion to The Journal of Clinical Psychiatry|volume=2|issue=1|pages=16–19|issn=1523-5998|pmid=15014663|via=}}</ref> Research also suggests a familial genetic connection of the temperament to [[Bipolar I disorder|bipolar I]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chiaroni|first=P.|last2=Hantouche|first2=E. G.|last3=Gouvernet|first3=J.|last4=Azorin|first4=J. M.|last5=Akiskal|first5=H. S.|date=November 2004|title=[Hyperthymic and depressive temperaments study in controls, as a function of their familial loading for mood disorders]|journal=L'Encephale|volume=30|issue=6|pages=509–515|issn=0013-7006|pmid=15738852}}</ref>
Aside from references in historical and more recent writings on the spectrum of mood disorders, further literature on the temperament is lacking.<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 8275895 | year = 1993 | author1 = Féline | first1 = A | title = Hyperthymic disorders | journal = L'Encéphale | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 103–7 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 11880944 | year = 2002 | author1 = Fritze | first1 = F | title = The concept of hyperthymia | journal = Fortschritte der Neurologie · Psychiatrie | volume = 70 | issue = 3 | pages = 117–25 | last2 = Ehrt | first2 = U | last3 = Brieger | first3 = P | doi = 10.1055/s-2002-20530 }}</ref> There is a lack of agreement on its definition, implications or whether it is [[pathological]]. It is not known where to place hyperthymia on the [[affective spectrum]].
Hyperthymia manifesting intermittently or in an unusual way may mask [[hypomania]] or another psychiatric disorder. Hyperthymia can be most accurately diagnosed by a psychologist or psychiatrist with the help of a patient's family and/or close friends.
==See also== * [[Euthymia (medicine)]] - stable, pleasant, tranquil, "normal" mood * [[Happiness]]
