{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = |name = Salma Kikwete |honorific-suffix = |image = Salma Kikwete.jpg |imagesize = |alt = |caption = |order = 4th | term_label = In role |office = First Lady of Tanzania |term_start = 21 December 2005 |term_end = 5 November 2015 |president = [[Jakaya Kikwete]] |taoiseach = |predecessor = [[Anna Mkapa]] |successor = [[Janeth Magufuli]] |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|11|30|df=y}} |birth_place = |birthname = |nationality = [[Tanzania]]n |party = [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi|CCM]] |spouse = {{Marriage|[[Jakaya Kikwete]]|1989}} |relations = |children = 5 |residence = [[Ikulu]], [[Dar es Salaam]] |alma_mater = |occupation = |profession = [[Teacher]] |cabinet = |committees = |portfolio = |religion = |signature = |signature_alt = |website = |footnotes = |blank1 = |data1 = }}
'''Salma Kikwete''' (born 30 November 1963) is a Tanzanian educator, activist, and politician who served as the [[First Lady of Tanzania]] from 2005 to 2015 as the wife of [[Tanzanian President]] [[Jakaya Kikwete]].<ref name=jis>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=Her Excellency Salma Kikwete|url=http://www.jis.gov.jm/special_sections/tanzania-visit-09/first-lady-profile.html|work=Jamaica Information Service|publisher=|date=2009-11-23|accessdate=2012-08-09|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804002412/http://www.jis.gov.jm/special_sections/tanzania-visit-09/first-lady-profile.html|archivedate=4 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Salma Kikwete originally worked as a teacher for more than twenty years.<ref name=jis/>
In 2005, the government launched a national campaign for voluntary [[HIV]]/[[AIDS]] testing in [[Dar es Salaam]]. Salma Kikwete and her husband were among the first in the country to be tested.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|first=|last=|title= Tanzanian leader takes Aids test |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6899134.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=|date=2007-07-14 |accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref> As of 2009, she was Vice President of the Eastern Region of the [[Organisation of African First Ladies against HIV/AIDS]] (OAFLA).<ref name=jis/> In 2012, the First Lady Salma Kikwete, former [[Botswana]] [[President of Botswana|President]] [[Festus Mogae]] and ten other African figures partnered with [[UNESCO]] and [[UNAIDS]] to support the Eastern and Southern Africa Commitment on HIV Prevention and Sexual Health for Young People, which was launched in November 2011.<ref name=unesco>{{cite news|first=|last=|title= Leaders to lobby for HIV Prevention and Sexual Health for Youth in Eastern and Southern Africa |url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/hiv-and-aids/single-view/news/leaders_to_lobby_for_hiv_prevention_and_sexual_health_for_youth_in_eastern_and_southern_africa/ |work=[[UNESCO]] |publisher=|date=2012-06-27 |accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref>
Kikwete also founded the ''Wanawake na Maendeleo'', or Women in Development (WAMA), a [[nonprofit]] which promotes development among women and children.<ref name=jis/>
Over a year after her husband left office, Salma Kikwete was appointed to a seat in the [[National Assembly of Tanzania|National Assembly]] by President [[John Magufuli]] on 1 March 2017.<ref>Esther Karin Mngodo, [http://allafrica.com/stories/201703030412.html "The Salma Kikwete story"], ''The Citizen'', 3 March 2017.</ref> ==References== {{reflist}}
