{{Infobox court case |name = State v. Strasburg |court = [[Washington Supreme Court]] |image = |imagesize = |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = The State of Washington v. Martin Strasburg |date decided = {{start date|1910|09|10}} |citations = 110 P. 1020, 60 Wash. 106, 1910 Wash. LEXIS 1016 |transcripts = |judges = [[Frank H. Rudkin|Rudkin]], [[Stephen J. Chadwick|Chadwick]], [[Herman D. Crow|Crow]], [[Mark A. Fullerton|Fullerton]], [[Mack F. Gose|Gose]], [[George E. Morris|Morris]], [[Wallace Mount|Mount]], [[Emmett N. Parker|Parker]] |number of judges = 9 |Majority = Parker |JoinMajority = Crow and Mount |concurring = Rudkin |JoinConcurrence = Gose and Chadwick; Dunbar joined in part |dissenting = Fullerton |concur/dissent = Morris |prior actions = |appealed from = [[Washington Superior Courts|Superior Court]] of [[King County, Washington|King County]] |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = {{hlist|Insanity defense|Right to jury trial|Due process|Legislation}} |italic title = }}
'''''State v. Strasburg''''', 110 P. 1020 (Wash. 1910), was a case decided by the [[Washington Supreme Court]] that held that a [[statute]] eliminating the [[insanity defense]] was unconstitutional. The court likened the exclusion of evidence of insanity to a denial of trial by jury.<ref>Bonnie, R.J. et al. ''Criminal Law, Second Edition.'' Foundation Press, New York: 2004, p. 623</ref>
Martin Strasburg, described as "an unknown and penniless stranger", was convicted of assault after shooting Otto Peeck in a saloon in Seattle. Lawyers saw the Strasburg case as an opportunity to have the Washington law that forbade insanity defenses declared unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news|title=May Knock Out Insanity Law|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3990512/leadup_to_decision_in_state_v/|accessdate=8 January 2016|work=Tacoma Times|agency=UPI|volume=7|issue=141|date=June 2, 1910|page=8|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> The effect of the Supreme Court declaring the law unconstitutional was said to be expected to reverse the convictions of "scores" of people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holds Insanity May Be Defense in Criminal Case|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3990507/holding_in_state_v_strasburg_announced/|accessdate=8 January 2016|work=Oregon Daily Journal|agency=UPI|volume=9|issue=163|date=September 12, 1910|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>
