[[Category:U.S. state criminal case law]] [[Category:1910 in United States case law]] [[Category:Washington (state) state case law]] [[Category:1910 in Washington (state)]] [[Category:United States jury case law]] [[Category:Insanity]] [[Category:Mental health law in the United States]]

'''Weather pains''', '''weather-related pain''', or '''meteoropathy''' is a phenomenon that occurs when people with conditions such as [[arthritis]] or limb injuries claim to feel pain, particularly with changes in [[barometric pressure]], [[humidity]] or other weather phenomena.<ref name="pain">[https://www.usatoday.com/weather/resources/safety/2005-02-21-health-pressure_x.htm Scientists still mulling causes of weather-related pain], by April Chan, USA Today</ref><ref name="about">[http://arthritis.about.com/od/weather/Weather_Arthritis_Barometric_Pressure_Affect_Humidity_Climate.htm Weather & Arthritis - Barometric Pressure Affect - Humidity - Climate], About</ref> Scientific evidence, however, does not support a connection between weather and arthritic pain and concludes that it is largely or entirely due to perceptual errors such as [[confirmation bias]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Smedslund|first1=G|last2=Hagen|first2=KB|title=Does rain really cause pain? A systematic review of the associations between weather factors and severity of pain in people with rheumatoid arthritis.|journal=European Journal of Pain|date=January 2011|volume=15|issue=1|pages=5–10|pmid=20570193|doi=10.1016/j.ejpain.2010.05.003}}</ref><ref name=MedicineNet>{{cite web|last1=Nazario|first1=Brunilda|title=Do Your Aches, Pains Predict Rain?|url=http://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=52133|website=Medicinenet.com|accessdate=22 October 2016}}</ref> The term is from Greek ''meteora'', celestial phenomena, and ''pathos'', feeling, pain, suffering.

==History==
The perceived relationship between changes in weather and pain has been recorded since the classical Roman age.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120912044051/http://www.iasp-pain.org/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Home&Template=%2FCM%2FContentDisplay.cfm&ContentID=2201  Influence of Weather on Report of Pain], by Robert N. Jamison, PhD, International Association for the Study of Pain Newsletter</ref> [[Hippocrates]] was the first to note, in about 400 B.C., that many illnesses were related to changes in season.<ref>Rosen S. Weathering. New York: M. Evans, 1979</ref> The large body of folklore about how weather affects pain is reflected by traditional sayings and expressions, such as "aches and pain, coming rains," "feeling under the weather," and "ill health due to evil winds."{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}

The first publication of documented changes in pain perception associated with the weather was in the ''American Journal of the Medical Sciences'' in 1887. This case report described a person with [[phantom limb]] pain who concluded that "approaching storms, dropping barometric pressure and rain were associated with increased pain complaint."<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite journal|authors=Shutty MS, Cunduff G, DeGood DE|title=Pain complaint and the weather: weather sensitivity and symptom complaints in chronic pain patients|journal=Pain|year=1992|volume=49|issue=2|pages=199–204|pmid=1608646|doi=10.1016/0304-3959(92)90143-Y}}</ref> Most investigations examining the relationship between weather and pain have studied people diagnosed with [[arthritis]]. After reviewing many case reports, Rentshler reported in the ''Journal of the American Medical Association'' in 1929 that there was strong evidence that "warm weather is beneficial and [[barometric pressure]] changes are detrimental to patients with arthritis."<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

Countering the 1929 barometric pressure claim, in a 2016 article entitled "Do Your Aches, Pains Predict Rain?" professor of atmospheric sciences Dennis Driscoll is reported as stating: "People need to realize that the pressure changes associated with storms are rather small." In fact, Driscoll observes that the changes associated with a storm are about equivalent to what a person experiences in going up an elevator in a tall building. So far, there have not been many reports of people with arthritis hobbled by elevator rides in the medical literature.<ref name=MedicineNet/>

A study published in the ''[[British Medical Journal]]'' in 2017 examined reports of joint or back pain from millions of doctor visits between 2008 and 2012 as recorded by [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], the U.S. health system for the elderly. It compared these to rain data as recorded by the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]], but found no correlation.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/12/20/the-rain-plain-has-effect-pain/THQuG8xZKv8r4QkEJHw6qL/story.html The rain, it’s plain, has no effect on pain]</ref>

==Non-English languages==
{{wiktionary}}

{{wiktionary|meteoropathy}}
The word ''meteoropathy'' is uncommon in English, but the concept and similar words are widespread in certain other languages. In [[Polish language|Polish]] a sufferer is a ''meteoropata'', in [[Italian language|Italian]] a ''meteoropatico'', in [[Croatian language|Croatian]] a ''meteoropat'',<ref>{{cite web|title=meteoròpāt|url=http://hjp.novi-liber.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=e1pkXxg%253D&keyword=meteoropat|publisher=hjp.novi-liber.hr|accessdate=21 June 2015}}</ref>[[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] a ''метеопат (meteopat)'', and [[Japanese language|Japanese]] a {{nihongo|''Kishō byō''|''気象病''}} for example.

